-- China stocks end up on policy optimism, property sector strong 
-- 
-- Wed Dec 03, 2014 02:13AM EST
-- None



SHANGHAI, Dec 3 (Reuters) - China stocks closed up on Wednesday after a volatile session, buoyed by solid gains in property firms and brokerages partly on speculation of more stimulus from Beijing.

The CSI300 index <.CSI300> of the largest listed companies in Shanghai and Shenzhen rose 1.5 percent, to 2,967.55 points, while the Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> gained 0.6 percent, to 2,779.53 points.  Among the most active stocks in Shanghai were Minsheng Bank <600016.SS>, up 4.2 percent at 8.24 yuan; Bank Of China <601988.SS>, down 4.49 percent at 3.40 yuan and Everbright Bank <601818.SS>, down 5.00 percent at 3.99 yuan. In Shenzhen, BOE Technology <000725.SZ>, up 5.1 percent at 2.90 yuan; TCL CORP <000100.SZ>, up 1.8 percent at 3.46 yuan and Changjiang Securities <000783.SZ>, up 4.8 percent at 11.34 yuan, were among the most actively traded. Foreign investment flowing into Shanghai from Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme took up 3.86 billion yuan ($627.9 million ) <.NQUOTA.SH> of the 13 billion yuan daily quota. Total volume of A shares traded in Shanghai was 56.1 billion shares, while Shenzhen volume was 28.8 billion shares.